Forensics Evidence Collection > [T1]: Lab - Evidence Collection: DumpIt

Lab Objectives

  1. Acquire a memory image on a live Windows system DumpIT.
  2. Ability to identify encrypted disk drives before proceeding with disk acquisition.
  3. Use Kroll Artifact Parser and Extractor (KAPE) to acquire a triage Image.
  4. Acquire different types of disk images using FTK Imager.
  5. Mount acquired Images using Arsenal Image Mounter.

1-Acquire a memory image on a live Windows system using DumpIt


To acquire a memory image, you will need to copy the acquisition tool (Dumpit in our case) to a USB stick and ensure that the USB stick's size is larger than the target machine's RAM size because the acquired memory image size will have the same size. In addition, you need to ensure that the USB stick is NTFS formatted.

 

Dumpit must be executed using an account with administrative privileges. To explore tool options, execute "Dumpit.exe /?" in the command line (cmd).

DumpIT help menu - (zoom in)

Executing "Dumpit.exe" without passing any option will automatically acquire a memory image and save it to the same place the tool was executed from. Type "Y" and wait for the tool to copy memory content.

DumpIT tool - (zoom in)

You will see the message "Processing" during the acquisition. Depending on the memory size and the write speed on the USB stick, it may take a couple of minutes to finish. If possible, use USB 3 sticks to save time.

Note: DumpIT will automatically close the terminal after completing the acquisition process. This is the default behavior.

 

Dumpit tool processing - (zoom in)

The next step is to ensure the output image is not corrupted. To do so, use Volatility (the tool you will use later to open the image and analyze it) to verify the image. Do not worry about "Volatility" at the moment. We will discuss it in detail in upcoming lessons.

 

The easiest way to verify that the image is working fine is by opening the image file and passing the "imageinfo" option, which lists the image's information.

 

Volatility output - (zoom in)
